			<div class="content" id="post-content-4043677">
									

<p>Thanks, Croquembouche - much appreciated.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>My only issue was the ending &#8230; to suddenly reclassify it as Thaumiel &#8230; doesn't make any sense &#8230;</p>
<p>There's nothing inherent to death itself that makes it worth protecting.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Just in case it's of any satisfaction:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Ending&nbsp;spoilers</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;collapse</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Death is only worth protecting in the same way that any Thaumiel would be maintained, or indeed any wall of any containment chamber in the Foundation.</p>
<p>Through experimenting with Amrita, the Foundation realises that death isn't something to be battled and overcome. Death is a natural (albeit unexplained) part of what protects existence - hence it is classified Thaumiel, as it actively prevents anomalies. Indeed, the search for immortality is a cause of many anomalies.</p>
<p>That's why it's the success of Amrita that is the problem for the Foundation, not its failure. That success is at the cost of humanity - O5-1 realises that his quest to conquer death has led him to kill or mutilate his friends and colleagues, and Lewis similarly loses touch with humanity because he won't experience life in the same way as them.</p>
<p>This is essentially a tragedy, and the final iteration is intended to end on a note of acceptance of death.</p>
<p>I hope that makes more sense.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

